## Plan (.3 eval-result caching/reuse — OPTIMIZATION only) — ATTEMPT 3

Revised across three gate reviews. Attempt 1 BLOCKED on (1) JudgeID matching had
to be STRICT equality (not empty-as-wildcard) and (2) the evaluator SEED had to
be in the cache key — both fixed in attempt 2 and CONFIRMED SOUND. Attempt 2
BLOCKED on a residual empty==empty hole — fixed here (FIX 3).

**Scope:** ONLY caching. Skip the expensive Judge call when an existing
EvalResult covers byte-identical, same-judge, same-seed inputs. NO change to
cohort (.1), the per-run pipeline boundary (.2), or win-rate/report (.4) beyond a
--no-cache flag and a CACHED marker. Replay+record still happen on every run
(boundary below); only the judge call is cached.

### CORE INVARIANT (FIX 3 — gate BLOCK, codex)
Cache reuse is enabled ONLY for judges with a known (NON-EMPTY) identity; an
UNIDENTIFIED judge (empty JudgeID) ALWAYS re-evaluates and is NEVER matched.
  - Attempt 2's strict equality still let empty-active == empty-cached count as a
    HIT. That is unsound: two DISTINCT unidentified judges (any non-ExecJudge —
    a stub, or a future identity-less judge) would reuse each other's verdicts
    via empty==empty. Latent cross-judge false-reuse.
  - FIX: caching requires a NON-EMPTY active JudgeID.
      * Active JudgeID EMPTY  => DO NOT perform a cache lookup at all; always run
        Evaluate. The eval doc is still WRITTEN (judge_id absent/empty) for
        provenance, but it can never be matched by anyone.
      * Active JudgeID NON-EMPTY => a hit requires an existing doc whose JudgeID
        is EXACTLY equal (plus seed + both targets + method).
  - Net effect: an empty-id doc is NEVER reused (a non-empty query can't equal
    empty; an empty-active query skips the lookup entirely). This fully closes
    the empty==empty hole.
  - In production the judge is always an *ExecJudge whose JudgeIdentity is a
    non-empty fingerprint, so this only hardens a latent path; normal
    `etude bench` behavior is unchanged.

### Replay-still-happens boundary (Q3) — CONFIRMED (gate-approved)
The cache key includes target B's Artifact sha (the REPLAY OUTPUT sha), which
only exists AFTER Runner.Run + Recorder.Record. So the cache CANNOT be checked
before replay. BenchRun (run.go) is unchanged through step 6 (resolve,
materialize, read orig, checkout, run, record). The cache lookup is INSERTED
between step 6 (record -> recorded.OutputArtifact known) and step 7 (build+run
pairwise eval). On HIT we skip steps 7-8 (Evaluate + Writer.Write); on MISS we
proceed exactly as today. This saves the expensive LLM judge call. Replay cost is
out of scope.

### Cache key (Q1) — correctness-critical (Seed included, gate-approved)
KEY = (Method="pairwise", Targets[0].Commit, Targets[0].Artifact,
Targets[1].Commit, Targets[1].Artifact, JudgeID [STRICT, non-empty], Seed). A hit
requires ALL of these to match exactly. Both targets are commit-pinned +
content-addressed (Artifact=sha256), so equal (Commit,Artifact) pairs ⇒
byte-identical inputs.

SEED IN THE KEY (gate BLOCK 2, confirmed): "deterministic" != "order-invariant."
perPairSwap exists PRECISELY BECAUSE judges may be POSITION-BIASED: a
deterministic-but-order-sensitive judge can return DIFFERENT canonical winners
for [A,B] vs [B,A] presentation. The seed chooses which presentation order a pair
gets (perPairSwap is a deterministic function of (Seed, ArtifactA, ArtifactB);
artifacts are already in the key), so a verdict cached under seed=X is NOT
necessarily valid under seed=Y. Different seed => MISS => re-judge. Same
(targets, judge, seed) => same orientation => same canonical verdict.

### Judge-identity gap (Q1) — record JudgeID; STRICT, non-empty-gated match
GAP CONFIRMED in code: run.go:203,230 set EvalResult.Producer = res.Producer
(the REPLAY producer), NOT the judge. Judge identity lives only in the CLI as
eval.ExecJudge{Command, Model} (bench.go resolveJudge) and reaches the judge
process as ETUDE_MODEL — it is NEVER persisted. So a persisted eval doc cannot
supply judge identity unless we add it. RESOLUTION:
  1. Add optional field EvalResult.JudgeID string (JSON "judge_id,omitempty"),
     additive to the v1 wire schema (omitempty => byte-identical output when
     empty). No version bump. Validate: if set, must be non-empty after trim;
     empty allowed (unidentified judge — provenance only, never matched).
  2. eval.JudgeIdentity(j Judge) string: for *ExecJudge return
     sha256("execjudge\x00"+strings.Join(Command,"\x00")+"\x00model="+Model)
     (full 64-hex). Non-ExecJudge/stub -> "" (no derivable identity). Computed
     CLI-side, threaded via Pipeline.JudgeID, written onto EvalResult.JudgeID on
     the MISS path.
  3. MATCHING — STRICT EQUALITY + NON-EMPTY GATE: lookup happens ONLY when the
     active JudgeID is non-empty; then a hit requires cachedDoc.JudgeID EXACTLY
     equal to it. empty active => no lookup (always evaluate). A known id never
     matches empty (no wildcard) and never matches a different known id.
     RATIONALE: you cannot safely reuse a verdict whose judge you don't know, and
     two distinct unidentified judges must not collide; there is NO legacy eval
     corpus to preserve (the only persisted eval docs were test artifacts, now
     deleted), so gating on non-empty identity costs nothing in practice and
     closes all cross-judge false-reuse paths.

### Where the cached doc's Seed comes from (REQUIRED for the seed match)
The query key carries the CURRENT run's Seed (Pipeline.Seed). To compare, each
CANDIDATE doc must also expose its Seed — but EvalResult does NOT record the seed
today. So we ALSO add an additive field:
  EvalResult.Seed *int64 (JSON "seed,omitempty"; pointer so absent != 0).
Written on the MISS path from Pipeline.Seed (the same seed passed to
PairwiseEvaluator{Seed:p.Seed}). Backward-compat: same omitempty additive
treatment as JudgeID — added to BOTH the Go struct and the evalResultJSON wire
struct so DisallowUnknownFields (result.go:246) still parses new docs; old docs
(no "seed" key) decode with Seed=nil. MATCHING w.r.t. seed: the active run always
has a concrete int64 seed; a candidate with Seed==nil cannot be proven to share
the orientation, so nil MISSES any concrete-seed query (strict, same spirit as
JudgeID). Docs written by this code path always carry a Seed, so this only
excludes pre-seed-field docs (none in practice).

### Soundness for non-deterministic judges (Q1 caveat) — unchanged
LLM judges are not deterministic; reusing a prior verdict for identical bytes is
a sampling shortcut. v1 makes caching default-ON, opt-out via --no-cache, and
docs state it assumes a judge whose canonical verdict is stable for identical
(inputs, orientation). DoubleJudge is not wired through bench; if a future flag
enables it, the key must also include a judge-mode marker. Recorded as follow-up.

### Hit detection (Q2) — where it lives + O(N)
NEW file internal/bench/cache.go (bench owns the bench cache; eval pkg stays
verdict-only). Signature:
  func lookupCachedEval(ctx, store refstore.Store, key cacheKey) (eval.EvalResult, bool, error)
Caller (BenchRun) skips this entirely when the active JudgeID is empty (FIX 3).
v1 = LINEAR SCAN: store.List(ctx, "refs/etude/evals") -> for each ref,
store.ReadFile(ctx, ref, "eval_result.json") -> eval.ParseJSON -> evaluate the
predicate (method + both (Commit,Artifact) pairs + STRICT non-empty JudgeID +
Seed). First match wins (List is sorted => deterministic). O(N) over all evals;
SQLite/secondary index DEFERRED and documented. Skip/continue on a single
malformed doc (one bad ref must not fail the whole bench run). cacheKey holds
method, the two ArtifactSource (Commit,Artifact) pairs, JudgeID (non-empty
string), and Seed (int64).

### Hit behavior (Q3) — unchanged
On HIT: BenchRun does NOT call evaluator.Evaluate and does NOT call Writer.Write
(no new ref). BenchOutcome is built from the CACHED doc: Winner=
cached.Score.Winner, Confidence=cached.Score.Confidence, Findings=
cached.Findings, EvalID=cached.EvalID (the EXISTING id), Result=cached, plus the
freshly recorded ReplayRunID/ReplayCommit from THIS run's replay. New field
BenchOutcome.Reused bool (true on hit) feeds .4's CACHED marker.
On MISS (including every empty-JudgeID run): unchanged — Evaluate, then
build+Validate+Write a new EvalResult that now also carries JudgeID (maybe empty)
and Seed; Reused=false.

### --no-cache flag + Pipeline seam (Q4, Q5) — unchanged
Pipeline gains: Cache bool (default true; false => always evaluate) and JudgeID
string (active fingerprint). Seed already exists on Pipeline. BenchRun performs a
lookup only when p.Cache is true AND p.JudgeID != "" (FIX 3). CLI (.4 bench.go):
add cmd.Flags().BoolVar(&noCache, "no-cache", false, "force re-evaluation; skip
the eval-result cache"); set Pipeline.Cache = !noCache and Pipeline.JudgeID =
eval.JudgeIdentity(activeJudge) at the existing construction (bench.go:131). No
other .4 behavior change; renderReport gains a CACHED indicator fed by
BenchOutcome.Reused (additive column/marker).

